Source: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.observer.co.uk/business/story/0,6903,855747,00.html">The Observer.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <br>
<br>
Energy Minister Brian Wilson has given the strongest hint yet that the government will build a new generation of nuclear power stations in the UK - with international collaboration if necessary.<br>
 <br>
In a parliamentary answer on Britain's role in a 10-nation research programme into Generation-IV nuclear reactors, he said: 'The aim is to develop a framework for collaborative R&amp;D to facilitate the deployment of such advanced reactor schemes from 2030 and beyond.' <br>
<br>
The Generation-IV programme, which includes the US, Brazil, France and Canada, aims to spread development costs to design financially viable nuclear power stations providing affordable electricity while maintaining the nuclear role in controlling carbon-dioxide emissions. The Government is drafting a White Paper in which it will detail its thinking on the need for new reactors. <br>
<br>
All but one of Britain's nuclear stations is due to close by 2020 causing emissions to rise from 2010. <br>
<br>
'This programme gives substance to our stated commitment to keep the nuclear option open,' said Wilson, who added it would not prejudge the White Paper or the decision to build stations in the UK. He continued: 'The British nuclear industry has suffered from lack of consistency in design, and if at some future date there is to be nuclear new-build, then it would be sensible to base it on a more uniform approach.' <br>
<br>
The programme is looking at six reactor designs to address concerns about the viability of nuclear energy. It is investigating how new plants can reduce the amount of spent fuel and waste to alleviate pressure on repositories for radioactive material. <br>
<br>
The question of nuclear power's future role in the UK is pressing for Wilson and Trade and Industry Secretary Patricia Hewitt. Under the Government's commitments to the Kyoto protocol, the emission of greenhouse gases must fall. <br>
<br>
However, the collapse of British Energy has posed fundamental question marks over the viability of plants. <br>
